{"type":"message","id":"7052e944","parentId":"ba3608f5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:10:14.709Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the log I read earlier wasn't the pulse log from this execution - it was a pre-existing file from 09:08. Let me check what files are in the session directory to find the actual log from this run.\n\nActually, looking at the process list, `quiet-claw` is the current pulse and it completed. The log output I saw earlier was the most recent log from the session directory. Let me re-read that file - it actually contained the content from the pulse.\n\nLooking at the content I read from `pulse_2026-03-24 090816.md`, it seems like it contained analysis content about TIC experiment, not a traditional pulse log. \n\nI'm noticing a mismatch between the log filename timestamp (090816) and the process completion time (~34s ago at 090914), which suggests this is actually an older file from a previous pulse cycle. The quiet-claw session that just finished should have generated a newer log, but the file I read appears to be from an earlier run.\n\nLooking at the pulse output itself, it seems the iteration attempted to create an `experiments/TIC/experiment_spec.md` file but only partially succeeded - the file was inferred as \"the\" rather than containing the full specification content, which suggests something went wrong during the file write operation. I'm noticing the filename pattern `pulse_2026-03-24 090816.md` is actually older than the 09:09 timestamp of the current cron job, so this appears to be a pre-existing file from a previous run. The cron job scheduled for 09:09 is the one that just executed, which should have created a newer file. Let me figure out which file was actually generated by this latest pulse cycle.","thinkingSignature":"d9e128352d9b5819e478c3d6d1467ee46af29521873c196447954901f4323912"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_k9bc5sb26zkm_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Chil